collation.p: VisColl collation. Quire 12 tentative, may consist of three singletons added to a quinternion. Parchment guards made of strips from an older manuscript.
collation.signatures: Quire signatures in the form of letters at the end of every quire. (Some hardly visible due to trimming.)

p.note: Top left corner: National Library book label with current signum.

binding.p: Medieval binding. Originally brown leather over bevelled wooden boards. 4 double raised bands and endbands. Brass corner and centre bosses. Two pin strap buckles. , remnants of an old label (text not legible) 5 paper labels wiht text in ink: 136 or 138; No 5. 1. Novium Testamentum Latine. 2. Historia ecclesiastica temporis Christi; stamped in gold: A 170; 5.; e. 30. 2. 5.; 131., 291?.
binding.condition: Leather very worn (original colour almost completely gone). One strap missing, the second may be renovated. Several bosses missing. Boards exposed on edges. Original pastedowns removed.

history.origin: Bohemia? Moravia? , 15th century. The scribe identifies himself (in a cryptic way) as Arnoldus on . The presence of phrases in Czech on and , as well as glosses on and indicates an origin in Bohemia or Moravia.
history.provenance: The manuscript has been at the National Library since at least the 17th century. It was probably taken as war booty during the Thirty Year's War. The labels on the spien refer to the old catalogues. It is listed in Jaches's catalogue of 1695 (U 118:10) as 131; in Jaches's catalogue of 1698 (U 122) as 291; and in the catalogue of 1734 (U 125e) as Libr. mscr. in fol. nr 5. Finally, in Hammarsköld’s 19th century catalogue (U 133) it is listed as e. 30. 2. 5..

supportDesc.condition: Some staining and wear throughout. Noticeable book worm damage in places, especially on (this indicates that the book may have been kept open at this section).

p.note: Top left corner, in black ink by a medieval hand: 20 lines of text in two paragraphs. The first paragraph ends with a reference to Thomas Aquinas.
Throughout marginal and occasionally interlinear additions by several medieval hands. The additions mainly seem to be corrections and become less frequent after the first half.
A marginal note and some interlinear glosses in Czech.
Chapter indentifications in pencil by a modern hand. On a note in Swedish attributed the text to to Petrus Comestor.
A note placed between and . One side of the note contains four partial lines of text in Czech by a medieval hand.
A note placed between and . One side of the note contains eight partial lines of text in ink by a medieval hand.
